---
import BaseLayout from "@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="How we evaluate skincare"
  description="The BES3 framework for reading claims and comparing skincare choices."
>
  <section class="page-hero shell">
    <div><p class="eyebrow">METHOD NOTE</p><h1>Evidence, fit, experience.</h1></div><p class="lede">
      BES3 uses three lenses so a product can be interesting without being right for everyone.
    </p>
  </section>
  <section class="section shell">
    <div class="proof-grid">
      <article>
        <p class="eyebrow">01 · EVIDENCE</p><strong>What can the information support?</strong><p>
          We look at the quality, relevance and limits of research, guidance and product
          documentation.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article>
        <p class="eyebrow">02 · FIT</p><strong>Who is it actually for?</strong><p>
          We consider skin concern, routine stage, texture, climate, use case and likely
          limitations.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article>
        <p class="eyebrow">03 · EXPERIENCE</p><strong>Can a person keep using it?</strong><p>
          When hands-on testing is real, we describe finish, texture and handling. Otherwise we
          label the page as analysis.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>
  <section class="section section--paper reading-width article-body">
    <h2>What we do not score</h2><p>
      We do not create a single numerical score that pretends skin, evidence and personal preference
      can be reduced to one decimal place. We use plain-language conclusions and explicit
      trade-offs.
    </p>
    <h2>Safety boundary</h2><p>
      BES3 is educational. Persistent, painful or changing skin concerns should be discussed with a
      qualified clinician.
    </p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
